{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17570156","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17570156"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:23+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T00:38:23+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22756"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"22756","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/22756"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.05,0.01,0.04,0.02,0.88]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15703"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111922"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"15703","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/15703"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22756"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93986"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"78"},{"type":"tags","id":"682"},{"type":"tags","id":"4961"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4992"},{"type":"tags","id":"5826"},{"type":"tags","id":"11630"},{"type":"tags","id":"11642"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"45678"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45679"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45680"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45681"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45682"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45689"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111922","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111922"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 50-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department after a head-on motor vehicle collision at 60 km/hr. She was the restrained passenger in the back seat and reports abdominal pain for one hour since the crash.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe describes constant, generalised abdominal pain worsened by movement and coughing. She denies chest pain or shortness of breath. She has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. She does not use alcohol or other substances. There is no recent travel.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears unwell. Her pulse rate is 120/min, blood pressure 90/50 mmHg, respiratory rate 20/min, SpO2 100% on 8 L oxygen via face mask, and temperature 36.6\u00b0C. She is in cervical spine precautions. On auscultation of the chest there is equal air entry to both bases. On abdominal examination bruising from the seatbelt is readily visible and abdominal palpation reveals mild diffuse tenderness (\u003Ca href=\u0022https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/L7lVnDqeVNRG9VKjTMKPH42HjWeowE.jpg\u0022\u003EImage\u003C/a\u003E).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe received intravenous fentanyl during transport. A bedside focused assessment with sonography for trauma is pending.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following structures is most likely to have been injured?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Small bowel","Colon","Pancreas","Liver","Spleen"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EBlunt abdominal trauma from rapid deceleration with a visible seatbelt sign is strongly associated with intra-abdominal injury. Early haemodynamic instability after such trauma typically reflects haemorrhage from a solid organ rather than an isolated hollow viscus injury. Among solid organs, the spleen is the most frequently injured in blunt trauma, and splenic laceration can produce significant intraperitoneal bleeding and shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESpleen\u003C/strong\u003E is the most likely source of haemorrhage in a hypotensive patient with blunt abdominal trauma, especially with a seatbelt mechanism and early tachycardia and hypotension. Splenic injury commonly causes intraperitoneal bleeding and accounts for the highest proportion of solid organ injuries in these scenarios.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESmall bowel\u003C/strong\u003E injury, including blow-out perforation, is a recognised consequence of seatbelt compression and rapid deceleration. However, isolated hollow viscus injury more often presents with delayed peritonism or subtle signs rather than immediate shock; brisk early shock more strongly indicates solid organ haemorrhage.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EColon\u003C/strong\u003E can be injured by seatbelt compression and deceleration with mesenteric tears or contusion, but, similar to small bowel injury, isolated colon injury is less likely to cause immediate haemodynamic instability compared with splenic bleeding.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPancreas\u003C/strong\u003E injury typically results from epigastric compression against the spine and often presents with delayed abdominal pain, rising serum amylase or lipase, and retroperitoneal findings rather than early intraperitoneal haemorrhage and shock.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELiver\u003C/strong\u003E injury is also common in blunt trauma and can cause significant bleeding; however, across large trauma series the spleen is injured most frequently in high-energy blunt abdominal trauma, and the combination of left upper quadrant vulnerability and rapid onset shock makes splenic injury more likely overall in this context.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["A visible seatbelt sign after high-speed deceleration is strongly associated with intra-abdominal injury and mandates urgent evaluation.","Haemodynamic instability after blunt abdominal trauma most commonly reflects splenic injury among solid organs.","Hollow viscus injuries can occur with seatbelt compression, but shock in the early phase more often suggests solid organ haemorrhage."],"references":["Pourmand A, Terrebonne E, Shapovalov V, et al. Prevalence of intra-abdominal injury among patients with seatbelt signs, a systematic review and meta-analysis. Am J Emerg Med 2024; 76:199\u2013206.","Masudi T, McMahon HC, Scott JL, et al. Seat belt\u2011related injuries: A surgical perspective. J Emerg Trauma Shock. 2017; 10:70-73","Shreffler J, Smiley A. Schultz M, et al. Patients with Abrasion or Ecchymosis Seat Belt Sign Have High Risk for Abdominal Injury, but Initial Computed Tomography is 100% Sensitive. J Emerg Med. 2020; 59:491-98."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93986"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"22756"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"22055"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"22055","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/22055"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/L7lVnDqeVNRG9VKjTMKPH42HjWeowE.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/L7lVnDqeVNRG9VKjTMKPH42HjWeowE.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":513,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93986","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93986"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-21T15:07:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-09-02T10:23:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"15703"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111922"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"24","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/24"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude91","name":"Emergency Medicine","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"65","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/65"},"attributes":{